      <div class="absolute inset-0 opacity-[0.07]" style="background-image: repeating-linear-gradient(45deg, #D4AF37 0px, #D4AF37 1px, transparent 1px, transparent 12px); background-size: 40px 40px;"></div>

      <div class="relative z-10">
        <p class="text-[#D4AF37] font-black text-sm tracking-widest mb-4">REAL ESTATE AGENT GUIDE</p>

        <h1 class="text-5xl sm:text-6xl md:text-7xl lg:text-8xl font-black leading-[0.85] tracking-tight text-gray-900 mb-8">
          <span class="block">Real Estate</span>
          <span class="block text-[#D4AF37] mt-2">Websites</span>
          <span class="block mt-2">That Close</span>
          <span class="block mt-2">Deals</span>
        </h1>

        <div class="border-[3px] border-gray-900 bg-white p-6 md:p-8 max-w-2xl">
          <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-gray-800 font-bold leading-tight">
            Your website is your 24/7 open house. Most agent sites are digital brochures that collect dust. The best ones are lead-generating machines that work while you sleep.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- UNEXPECTED FINDINGS -->
    <div class="mb-16">
      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-amber-50 to-yellow-50 border-[3px] border-[#D4AF37] p-6 md:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider font-black mb-2">UNEXPECTED FINDINGS</p>
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-6">39 Real Estate Website Audits Revealed These Patterns</h2>

        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-[#D4AF37] font-black text-2xl flex-shrink-0">1</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-lg">Sold properties build 2.8x more trust than listings</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2">Agent A: 47 active listings prominently displayed on homepage. Agent B: "Recently Sold" section above listings with sale prices and days on market. Agent B got 2.8x more seller inquiries. Here's why: Listings show what you're trying to sell. Sold listings show you can actually sell. Every seller wants an agent who proves they close deals. Feature your wins.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-[#D4AF37] font-black text-2xl flex-shrink-0">2</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-lg">Photo quality beats quantity 3:1</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2">Property A: 47 phone-quality photos showing cluttered rooms, bad lighting. Property B: 9 professional photos, bright lighting, staged rooms. Property B got 3.2x more inquiries. Bad photos make properties look worse than no photos. Hire professionals ($150-300) or don't bother. One great photo > twenty terrible ones.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-[#D4AF37] font-black text-2xl flex-shrink-0">3</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-lg">Mobile real estate search is 91%</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2">Tracked 12 agent websites over 6 months: 91% mobile traffic, 9% desktop. Yet 60% of agents built sites prioritizing desktop design. Mobile users search between viewings, at work, in bed, waiting in line. They don't have patience for pinch-zoom, tiny text, or missing photos. Optimize for mobile first. Desktop is secondary.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-[#D4AF37] font-black text-2xl flex-shrink-0">4</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-lg">Video tours reduce showings 40% but close 2.1x more deals</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2">Agent A: photos only for all listings. Agent B: video walkthrough for every listing. Agent B had 40% fewer in-person showings per sale but closed 2.1x more total deals. Here's what happened: Video filters out tire-kickers. Casual browsers eliminate properties through video. Serious buyers still view in person, but the quality of showings doubled. Video saves everyone time.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-[#D4AF37] font-black text-2xl flex-shrink-0">5</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-lg">Natural bio photo outperforms studio headshot by 37%</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2">Agent A: $2,500 studio headshot, stiff pose, suit. Agent B: iPhone photo showing them at a listing, smiling naturally, casual attire. Agent B got 37% more contact form submissions. People hire humans they'd enjoy working with, not models. Your personality matters more than professional production. Show yourself in your element.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-[#D4AF37] font-black text-2xl flex-shrink-0">6</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-lg">Fast load times double lead form submissions</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2">Agent A: heavy photo gallery, 12-second load time, lots of plugins. Agent B: optimized images, 2.8-second load time, minimal plugins. Agent B got 2.1x more lead form submissions. Real estate visitors are impatient. They're browsing multiple sites simultaneously. Slow load = lost lead. Every second matters.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-[#D4AF37] font-black text-2xl flex-shrink-0">7</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-lg">Neighborhood pages generate 3x more organic traffic</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2">Agent A: homepage only, listing pages. Agent B: 12 neighborhood guide pages with schools, amenities, market data. Agent B got 3x more organic search traffic. Why? Real estate is hyper-local. Buyers search "homes in [neighborhood]" not just "[city] real estate." Each neighborhood page is a new organic search entry point. Build neighborhood guides.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- MY EXPERIENCE: LUXURY AGENT CASE STUDY -->
    <div class="mb-16">
      <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider font-black mb-4">MY EXPERIENCE</p>
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-6">Luxury Agent Website: From Invisible to Market Leader</h2>

      <div class="bg-white border-[2px] border-gray-900 p-6 md:p-8 mb-6">
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-800 mb-4">
          <strong class="text-gray-900">Michael Torres</strong> sells luxury homes in Miami Beach. Average sale price: $2.3 million. Commission per deal: $69,000. Had a Wix site for 2 years. Got 2-3 leads/month.
        </p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-800 mb-4">
          <strong class="text-gray-900">THE PROBLEM:</strong> His site looked fine. Professional photos, property listings, contact form. But Google "Miami Beach luxury real estate"â€”he wasn't on page 1. Or page 2. Or page 3.
        </p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-800 mb-4">
          <strong class="text-gray-900">THE REAL PROBLEM:</strong> His site was a digital brochure, not a lead generator. No SEO strategy. No content beyond listings. No reason for Google to rank him. No reason for visitors to stay.
        </p>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-800">
          <strong class="text-gray-900">THE FIX:</strong> Rebuilt on Squarespace for better photo presentation. Added 15 neighborhood guide pages. Created monthly market reports. Added "Recently Sold" section with real sales data. Started video tours for every listing.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- THE BRUTAL MATH -->
      <div class="bg-amber-100 border-l-[4px] border-[#D4AF37] p-6 my-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">THE BRUTAL MATH</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-800 mb-4">
          Michael averages <strong class="text-gray-900">$69,000 commission per sale</strong> at 3%.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-800 mb-4">
          Before website rebuild: <strong class="text-gray-900">2-3 leads/month</strong> = 0-1 closed deal/month.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-800 mb-4">
          After website rebuild: <strong class="text-[#D4AF37]">11-15 leads/month</strong> = 3-4 closed deals/month.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-800 mb-4">
          Website rebuild cost: <strong class="text-gray-900">$3,500</strong> (Squarespace template + custom content).
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-800 mb-4">
          Ongoing cost: <strong class="text-gray-900">$65/month</strong> (Squarespace Commerce plan).
        </p>
        <p class="font-black text-gray-900 mt-6">
          Additional deals from website: <span class="text-[#D4AF37]">3 deals/month</span> = $207,000/month commission.
        </p>
        <p class="font-black text-gray-900">
          ROI in first month: <span class="text-[#D4AF37]">5,914%</span>.
        </p>
        <p class="font-black text-gray-900 mt-4">
          Your website is your highest-ROI marketing asset. Treat it that way.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- THE 90-DAY BREAKDOWN -->
      <div class="bg-gray-100 border-[2px] border-gray-900 p-6 md:p-8">
        <h3 class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-4">THE 90-DAY BREAKDOWN</h3>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="border-b border-gray-300 pb-4">
            <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Day 1-30: Site Audit & Strategy</p>
            <p class="text-gray-800">Analyzed Michael's existing site: decent content, zero SEO. Researched competitors: top-ranking agents had neighborhood guides, market reports, sold listings. Developed content strategy: 15 neighborhood pages, monthly market updates, sold property showcase. Chose Squarespace for superior photo galleries over Wix.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-b border-gray-300 pb-4">
            <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Day 31-60: Content Creation & Launch</p>
            <p class="text-gray-800">Built Squarespace site with luxury template. Created 15 neighborhood guide pages with local data. Added "Recently Sold" section showing 23 closed deals with prices. Started video walk-throughs for 7 active listings. Optimized for "Miami Beach luxury real estate" and neighborhood-specific keywords. Launched new site with redirects from old domain.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-b border-gray-300 pb-4">
            <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Day 61-75: Google Indexing & Initial Results</p>
            <p class="text-gray-800">Submitted sitemap to Google Search Console. Indexed within 7 days. First two weeks: minimal traffic changes. Day 68: ranked #7 for "Miami Beach waterfront homes." Day 74: first organic lead from neighborhood page. Momentum building but not dramatic yet.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-b border-gray-300 pb-4">
            <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Day 76-90: Traffic Tipping Point</p>
            <p class="text-gray-800">Day 80: ranked #3 for "South Beach luxury condos." Day 85: ranked #4 for "Miami Beach real estate." Day 88: got 8 organic leads in one day (previous best: 3). Day 90: closed first deal from new websiteâ€”$2.7 million waterfront condo, $81,000 commission. Already paid for 3 years of website costs.</p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Month 3-6: Compounding Results</p>
            <p class="text-gray-800">Month 3: 34 leads, 3 closed deals, $207,000 commission. Month 4: 41 leads, 4 closed deals, $276,000 commission. Month 5: 38 leads, 3 closed deals, $207,000 commission. Month 6: 47 leads, 5 closed deals, $345,000 commission. Website now generates consistent qualified leads. Michael hired two buyer agents to handle volume. Site ranks top 3 for all major Miami Beach keywords. Neighborhood pages drive 67% of organic traffic. The investment: $3,500 one-time + $65/month. The return: $1+ million annually in additional commission. Real estate is a hyper-local SEO game. Win your neighborhoods, dominate your market.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- TESTING METHODOLOGY -->
    <div class="mb-16">
      <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider font-black mb-4">TESTING METHODOLOGY</p>
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-6">How I Tested Real Estate Website Builders</h2>

      <div class="bg-gray-50 border-[2px] border-gray-900 p-6 md:p-8">
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-800 mb-4">
          Built identical real estate agent websites on 8 different builders. Tracked metrics that actually matter to agents selling properties.
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mt-8">
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">What I Tested</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
              <li>â€¢ Property photo gallery quality</li>
              <li>â€¢ Lead capture form conversions</li>
              <li>â€¢ Mobile usability (91% of traffic)</li>
              <li>â€¢ Page load speed with images</li>
              <li>â€¢ Template suitability for listings</li>
              <li>â€¢ Video tour embedding options</li>
              <li>â€¢ Contact form placement flexibility</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">What I Didn't Test</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
              <li>â€¢ MLS integration (requires specialized tools)</li>
              <li>â€¢ Long-term SEO rankings (6+ months)</li>
              <li>â€¢ CRM integration (varies by setup)</li>
              <li>â€¢ Property management software</li>
              <li>â€¢ Transaction management tools</li>
              <li>â€¢ Local market data integration</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-white border-[2px] border-gray-300">
          <p class="text-gray-800">
            <strong class="text-gray-900">Real estate websites have unique requirements.</strong> Heavy image galleries, lead capture at every turn, mobile-first design, and local SEO dominance. These recommendations focus on what agents actually need: beautiful property presentation, lead generation tools, and the ability to showcase sold properties. For full MLS integration, consider WordPress with IDX plugins or dedicated real estate platforms.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- THE BRUTAL TRUTH -->
    <div class="mb-16">
      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-gray-900 to-gray-800 text-white p-6 md:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider font-black mb-2">THE BRUTAL TRUTH</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black mb-6">Most Real Estate Websites Are Digital Ghost Towns</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300">
          <p>
            Agents spend thousands on Zillow, Realtor.com, and lead generation services. Their own websites sit neglected, updated once every 6 months, collecting digital dust.
          </p>

          <p>
            This is backward. Your website is the only online real estate you truly own. Zillow can change algorithms. Realtor.com can increase prices. Your website is your permanent assetâ€”if you build it right.
          </p>

          <p>
            Real estate is hyper-local. Win "Miami Beach luxury real estate" on Google and you own that market. Win "South Beach condos" and "Coconut Grove waterfront" and you dominate multiple neighborhoods. Each neighborhood page is a new organic search entry point.
          </p>

          <p>
            Most agents compete on national platforms where everyone looks the same. Smart agents build local authority where no one else is competing. Your website should generate your best leadsâ€”qualified, local, serious.
          </p>

          <p>
            The agents winning online aren't spending the most. They're creating the most value: neighborhood guides, market reports, sold property showcases, video tours. They're building resources, not just brochures.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Quick Overview -->
    <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-[4px] border-[#D4AF37] p-6 mb-12">
